My better idea is not to worry so much about intermediate
gravity checks.  Unless you're having problems with sluggish
fermentation, just a bit of experience (and patience) will
let you know when your beer has fermented out.  In most
cases, letting it ferment in a primary fermenter until you
think it's done (7-10 days after fermentation kicks in for
"normal" ales), racking to a secondary fermenter to clear
(take a gravity reading here for reassurance), and letting
clear in the secondary should get you a fully-fermented beer.
IMO the "check gravity every day to make sure it's done"
advice is overkill, and opens up the batch to infection.
--
