This is what I do. With a 3 gallon batch in a 5 gallon
carboy I don't feel there is enough CO2 generated
to guarantee that the 2 gallon air space will be
purged of oxygen. I wait until fermentation has
slowed significantly then rack to a 3 gallon carboy
to let it complete fermentation and then clear.
After that I will rack to a 5 gallon bucket with
priming sugar to bottle. At each rack I'll leave
some sludge behind. It's right before I bottle
that I check the FG.

As John mentioned I do it to ensure I don't have
a stuck fermentation. I did it once with a wine
kit and ended up putting in the potassium
metabisulphite at 1.010. It took me 4 months to
get the fermentation going again by aerating
and using hydrogen peroxide.

