A hydrometer reading saved a batch for me last week.

I did a 10 gallon all grain "New Old Ale"
( http://northernbrewer.com/docs/kis-html/1503.html - had to substitute
priming sugar for dark Belgian candi sugar - was not shipped) which has
Wyeast #1084, Irish Ale yeast. Claims optimum ferment temp down to 62 F.
Brew day went fine, no problems.

I was able to chill it down to about 65 F (brewing in the garage in
winter heh) and put it downstairs, set the downstairs thermometer (we
have a bi-level) to 65 F and let it be for a week. After a week airlock
activity suggested it was just about done, so I set the thermostat on
its usual schedule (58 at night 63 during the day unless we are down
there, and I manually set it to 66-68). Anyhow, I keg my beers and have
as of late have been skipping secondary fermentation, just leaving it
in primary for 3 or so weeks and racking into the kegs. So, after three
or so weeks from brew day I get ready to keg. I notice that the beer
is more cloudy than I am used to. As I always do, I rack a glass to
taste as I fill the first keg - holy crap it's still way to sweet! I
take a hydro reading - 1.035 (down from 1.070 but still). Oh no, are
we stuck?? Change of plan time! I excise my kegged lagering Maibock
from the temp-controlled chest freezer (it's ready anyhow) and put the
2 cornies in the kegerator. I rack both old ales into secondary, wipe
out the inside of the freezer, drop 'em in there, and scrounge up my
portable aluminum clip-on utility light (takes one regular light bulb).
Put a 100 W bulb in it, switch the temperature controller to from cool
to heat, set it to 72 F, wrap both carboys in lots of towels to block
the light, close the lid, switch it on and cross my fingers.

I check the freezer a few hours later, temp is almost up to 70 (from 33
mind you).

Next day it's actively fermenting again - about one bloop every 10-20
seconds.

Now, I probably shocked the buggers a bit but I think it will be fine.
Had I kegged this beer, it would have been cloyingly sweet. So taking
a reading at kegging/bottling time is recommended. Sometimes I don't -
if it tastes fabulous out of primary I don't see the need except for
curiosity's sake. I am a somewhat lazy brewer :)

Leigh

