This is something that is often misunderstood.  While CO2 is heavier
than O2, the two gasses will mix completely.  That is, if you were to
take a bottle and fill the lower half with pure CO2 and the top half
with O2 and just let it sit (persumably at a temperature and pressure
where both were gas) you would end up with bottle whose contents had a
uniform compositon of 50% CO2 and 50% O2.

If you transfer while the wort is actively fermenting, while the
evolving CO2 will help purge any O2 that exists in the headspace, it
takes a long time (quite possibly longer than the fermentation will
last).  The Oxygen will also diffuse into the wort at the same time.
If the wort is actively fermenting, however, the yeast will metabolize
any O2 that actually makes its way into the wort, preventing
oxidation.  That is why, if I can't transfer it to the 2ndry while the
fermentation is still active, I just leave it alone.

ab
